      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It seems noteworthy that in the same Jan. 30 edition your International report carries an article on United States plans to facilitate export logging in Siberia, and in Science Times you report on the melting of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet because of atmospheric warming.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It seems noteworthy that in the same Jan. 30 edition your International report carries an article on United States plans to facilitate export logging in Siberia, and in Science Times you report on the melting of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet because of atmospheric warming.</p>
        <p>The taiga, or boreal forest, of Siberia and the Russian Far East is the most extensive area of forest left on the planet and is thought to be a carbon "pool" that helps to regulate global climate. The Pacific Environment and Resources Center, which your article mentions, is one of the few groups working  to put this issue before the world community.</p>
        <p>If the United States Government and transnational timber interests work merely to exploit the taiga to feed the global pulp and timber markets without considerations of sustainability, we could end up subsidizing further destabilization of the global climate and a resulting rise in sea levels. We who live in deltas know that our margin of comfort is already slim.</p>
        <p>DOUG DAIGLE Baton Rouge, La., Jan. 30, 1996</p>
        <p>Program Director, Coalition to Restore Coastal Louisiana</p>
      </block>
